# LexMastery Engineering Philosophy

## Mission

LexMastery exists to become the world's most intelligent legal education platform.

The product combines Artificial Intelligence, cognitive science, structured learning, and premium user experience to help aspiring lawyers successfully prepare for professional legal examinations including:

- SQE
- NextGen Bar
- Future international legal qualifications

The application should never feel like an e-learning platform.

Instead, it should feel like an elite legal mentor.

Every engineering decision must reinforce this mission.

---

# Product Vision

LexMastery is not a course marketplace.

LexMastery is not a chatbot.

LexMastery is not another quiz application.

LexMastery is an AI-powered legal learning ecosystem.

The application should progressively evolve into the world's best AI legal education platform.

Every feature must contribute toward:

• confidence

• clarity

• mastery

• measurable progress

---

# Engineering Philosophy

Code should optimize for:

Readability

Maintainability

Scalability

Consistency

Accessibility

Performance

Security

Developer Experience

Never optimize prematurely.

Never sacrifice readability.

Always build reusable systems.

Never duplicate business logic.

---

# UX Philosophy

Users are preparing for one of the hardest examinations in their lives.

The application must reduce anxiety.

Never create visual clutter.

Never overwhelm users.

Guide them one decision at a time.

Always communicate progress.

Celebrate milestones.

Reduce cognitive load.

---

# Design Philosophy

Visual language:

Premium

Editorial

Professional

Academic

Minimal

Elegant

Never playful.

Never cartoonish.

Never childish.

Never flashy.

Avoid unnecessary gradients.

Avoid visual noise.

Whitespace is a feature.

---

# AI Philosophy

AI is a mentor.

Not a gimmick.

Not entertainment.

AI interactions should feel:

Thoughtful

Reliable

Professional

Transparent

Every AI response should inspire trust.

Where applicable:

show reasoning

show legal references

show confidence indicators

allow follow-up questions

---

# Mobile Experience

Design mobile-first.

Support tablets.

Support landscape where appropriate.

Respect safe areas.

Support accessibility.

Support offline learning whenever feasible.

Optimize for one-handed usage.

---

# Performance Philosophy

The application should feel instant.

Preferred targets:

Cold startup <2 seconds

Navigation <300ms

Animations 60 FPS

Avoid unnecessary rebuilds.

Lazy load expensive screens.

Cache aggressively.

---

# Accessibility

Accessibility is not optional.

Support:

Screen readers

Dynamic font sizes

Reduced motion

High contrast

Large touch targets

Semantic labels

WCAG AA compliance

---

# Engineering Standards

Prefer composition over inheritance.

Prefer immutable models.

Prefer dependency injection.

Never place business logic inside widgets.

Widgets should remain lightweight.

Feature code must remain isolated.

All APIs must go through repositories.

---

# Product Decisions

Every feature should answer:

Does this reduce study friction?

Does this improve learning?

Does this improve retention?

Does this improve exam performance?

If not,

reconsider building it.

---

# Cursor Instructions

Whenever generating code:

Act as a Senior Flutter Engineer.

Act as a Senior Product Designer.

Act as a Senior UX Designer.

Act as a Senior Software Architect.

Generate production-ready code.

Never generate placeholder architecture.

Prefer reusable widgets.

Prefer reusable themes.

Follow Clean Architecture.

Follow Feature-First Architecture.

Follow all project rules.

If a conflict exists between files,

the newest rule overrides the older rule.

Never ignore these principles.